From 39049db4121a3ed51c970176d25d63bc181a492c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jack Thomson <jackabt@amazon.com>
Date: Thu, 30 Apr 2026 15:32:45 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 93/94] KVM: x86: Add exitless async page fault notification
 via eventfd

When a VMM handles many userfault APFs (e.g. during snapshot restore),
the KVM_RUN exit/re-entry overhead for each fault becomes significant.

Add an exitless notification path: KVM writes APF details to a shared
ring buffer and signals an eventfd instead of exiting. The vCPU is
auto-halted and the APF auto-accepted, so the handler can resolve the
page and signal completion via the completion ring and eventfd without
any vCPU exits.

Fall back to the normal KVM_EXIT_MEMORY_FAULT path if the notify ring is
full.

The shared page is allocated by the kernel and mmap'd by userspace via
the vCPU fd at offset KVM_APF_PAGE_OFFSET * PAGE_SIZE, matching the
pattern used by the dirty ring and coalesced MMIO. It contains notify
and complete rings of 64 entries each.

Ring indices are free-running u32 counters; producer/consumer mask by
KVM_APF_RING_SIZE - 1 only when indexing into entries[], matching
kvm_dirty_ring and io_uring conventions. Completion is driven by a
workqueue kicked from an exclusive priority wait-queue entry on the
completion eventfd, mirroring irqfd dispatch.

Correctness and performance refinements folded into this patch:

  * kvm_async_pf_setup_userfault() combines exists-check + enqueue +
    exitless signal in a single lock hold.
  * kvm_async_pf_drain_complete_ring() drains a bounded batch under one
    lock, issues one vCPU wake, and reschedules itself if userspace raced
    in more completions.
  * Completion eventfd wakeups consume the eventfd counter and return the
    proper exclusive-waiter result.
  * Notify eventfd signaling is done for every published entry to avoid a
    lost-wakeup race with userspace consuming the ring.
  * KVM_SET_APF_EVENTFD rejects registration changes while APFs are
    pending on the vCPU.

Signed-off-by: Jack Thomson <jackabt@amazon.com>
